The dumbest thing in economics, the US government=E2=80=99s debt ceiling, i=
s clattering into relevance again. Basically the US Department of the Treas=
ury has to pay the US government=E2=80=99s bills, and to do that it issues =
debt, and every time it issues new debt it adds a little to the total amoun=
t of debt outstanding, and=C2=A0eventually the debt outstanding reaches som=
e arbitrary number called=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Cdebt ceiling.=E2=80=9D And then=
 Treasury can=E2=80=99t issue any more debt, unless Congress raises the deb=
t ceiling. Which it can easily do =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just an arbit=
rary number! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0Republicans in Congress keep threateni=
ng not to,=C2=A0and if that happens=C2=A0then the government=C2=A0can=E2=80=
=99t pay its bills and defaults on its obligations. Here is a recent speech=
 from Assistant Secretary of the Treasury Joshua Frost with more detail on =
why the debt ceiling is dumb and why Congress should raise it.
But there is a real risk that Congress=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t, so=C2=A0today Bl=
oomberg Opinion contributor=C2=A0Matt Yglesias has a Substack column arguin=
g that=C2=A0Treasury should solve the problem of the debt ceiling using pre=
mium bonds. I think this is correct, I have made this  argument a few times=
 before, and Yglesias clearly explains why the debt ceiling is very dumb an=
d why Treasury should, if need be, use gimmicks to solve it. And as gimmick=
s go,=C2=A0this one is fine. But his bond math is a little odd=C2=A0so I wa=
nted to walk through a simplified version=C2=A0here.
Assume that the US Treasury, these days, can issue a one-year bond at an in=
terest rate of 4.5%; that is not quite right but good enough.
  [1]
=C2=A0Simplistically,=C2=A0you pay Treasury $100 today, and in a year, Trea=
sury pays you back your $100, and also $4.50 of interest.
  [2]
=C2=A0When this bond is issued, it increases the government=E2=80=99s debt =
by $100, the face amount of the bond.
  [3]
=C2=A0
You could imagine a debt ceiling that worked a different way: You could ima=
gine counting this bond as adding $104.50 to the debt, since that is the to=
tal amount that the government has to pay back in principal and interest. B=
ut that would be sort of economically nonsensical, and anyway it is not the=
 way the actual debt ceiling works. The actual US debt ceiling statute caps=
 =E2=80=9Cthe face amount of obligations=E2=80=9D issued or guaranteed by t=
he government, meaning the principal=C2=A0amount, not the interest it has t=
o pay. Principal repayment obligations count toward the debt ceiling; inter=
est obligations do not.
Of course, you could pay Treasury $200 today to buy=C2=A0two=C2=A0of these =
one-year, $100, 4.5% bonds. That would increase the debt stock by $200. And=
 in a year you=E2=80=99d get back $209: your $200, plus 4.5% interest on yo=
ur $200.
The premium-bond gimmick is: Treasury sells you=C2=A0one one-year $100 bond=
 today, with an interest rate of 109%. In a year you get back $209: the $10=
0 face amount of the bond, plus 109% interest. That bond has a face amount =
of $100, but it is clearly=C2=A0worth=C2=A0$200 today: It is economically t=
he same as the two 4.5% bonds from the previous paragraph. So you=E2=80=99d=
 be willing to pay Treasury $200 for it: the $100 face amount, plus $100 of=
 =E2=80=9Cpremium=E2=80=9D to make the yield work out. And Treasury would b=
e willing to sell it to you for $200: It sells you this $100 bond for $200.=
 Treasury gets $200 of cash. But technically this bond is only $100 of =E2=
=80=9Cdebt,=E2=80=9D of face amount, so it only increases the debt by $100.
You can do this for other maturities,=C2=A0with slightly more math. Today t=
he 10-year Treasury note yield is about 3.6%. Instead of paying $100 for a =
10-year Treasury note that pays a normal=C2=A0annual interest rate ($3.60 p=
er year) and pays back $100 at maturity, you could pay $200 for a 10-year T=
reasury note that pays normal annual interest=C2=A0plus=C2=A0$10 per year, =
and pays back $100 at maturity. You get your $200 back =E2=80=94=C2=A0$10 p=
er year for 10 years plus $100 at the end =E2=80=94=C2=A0plus interest on y=
our money. But that $10 per year of principal return is called=C2=A0interes=
t, and treated as interest for the debt ceiling. (The way the math actually=
 works is that this bond would have about a 15.6% interest rate, that is, y=
ou=E2=80=99d get back about $15.60 per year plus $100 at the end.
  [4]
) It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a =E2=80=9C$100 bond=E2=80=9D for purposes of calculati=
ng how much debt is outstanding, but it=E2=80=99s worth $200.=C2=A0So, agai=
n, Treasury can raise $200 by selling $100 of debt.=C2=A0
So every time $100 of debt comes due, Treasury can pay it back by selling $=
100 of debt for $200, keep the extra $100 to pay its expenses, and render t=
he debt ceiling irrelevant.
Does this work? I have written about it a few times before, ages ago, and m=
y rough sense is =E2=80=9Cmeh, sure, probably.=E2=80=9D Nobody likes it, bu=
t neither has anyone ever pointed me to anything that makes it=C2=A0impossi=
ble. Again, the=C2=A0debt limit statute=C2=A0applies to =E2=80=9Cthe face a=
mount of obligations=E2=80=9D issued by the government, so a bond with a $1=
00 face amount sold for $200 would count for only $100 of debt. The law als=
o allows the Treasury to issue bonds =E2=80=9Cat any annual interest rate,=
=E2=80=9D and to decide =E2=80=9Cthe offering price and interest rate=E2=80=
=9D of any issuance. So I think if the Treasury secretary said =E2=80=9Cwe=
=E2=80=99re going to sell $100 face amount of 10-year bonds for $200 and pa=
y a 15.6% interest rate on them,=E2=80=9D that is quite gimmicky but also=
=C2=A0pretty clearly=C2=A0allowed by the statute. If Treasury did it, someo=
ne would probably sue, but I don=E2=80=99t think they=E2=80=99d have a very=
 good case; the law gives Treasury a lot of flexibility.
Now, Treasury itself=C2=A0has rules about debt issuance that do=C2=A0not=C2=
=A0really allow this; the current rules generally require Treasury to issue=
 notes and bonds at a price of par ($100 for a $100 face amount) or less.
  [5]
=C2=A0But those rules are set by the Treasury and can be changed in its dis=
cretion, without any act of Congress or any sort of administrative procedur=
e; the rules say: =E2=80=9CWe reserve the right to modify the terms and con=
ditions of new securities and to depart from the customary pattern of secur=
ities offerings at any time.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The main problems people have with this idea are in the general category of=
 =E2=80=9Cmarket reaction=E2=80=9D: Investors would not like this because i=
t=E2=80=99s a weird gimmick, they would worry about it being somehow invali=
d, etc., so they would require higher yields and thus increase the governme=
nt=E2=80=99s borrowing cost and interest rates generally. It=E2=80=99s impo=
rtant to note that, in my simple math above, the government=E2=80=99s borro=
wing costs have=C2=A0not=C2=A0increased: The 15.6% interest rate on my hypo=
thetical 10-year bond, or the 109% interest rate on my hypothetical one-yea=
r bond, do=C2=A0not=C2=A0represent more expensive borrowing than the curren=
t rates of 3.6% for a 10-year or 4.5% for a one-year; they just represent a=
ccounting gimmicks. In my hypothetical math, Treasury is paying the same ac=
tual yields on the actual money it raises; those high interest rates are ju=
st to shift principal repayment (covered by the debt ceiling) into interest=
 (not covered). But in reality investors might also=C2=A0charge a bit more;=
 the 10-year rate might really be, you know, 15.8%. That would be bad.
It=E2=80=99s hard to know how much of an effect this would have; it has nev=
er happened and no one has clear intuitions for it.=C2=A0In general, very-h=
igh-premium bonds tend to be worth a bit less than normal bonds,
  [6]
=C2=A0mostly for credit reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0a bond with $100 face amount=
 and very high interest that trades at $200 will only pay back $100 in bank=
ruptcy =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s not clear that that worry would appl=
y to US government debt. (Similarly, people worry that high-premium Treasur=
ies would be hard to finance in the repo market, but it=E2=80=99s not obvio=
us why that would be permanently true if the market concluded that Treasury=
 was good for the money.) But investors might worry that somehow these bond=
s=C2=A0would=C2=A0be invalidated and they wouldn=E2=80=99t get their intere=
st payments, and that risk would require a higher yield.
Anyway as a matter of financial engineering I find this fun to think about.=
 As an actual thing for the US Treasury to do, I think it is obviously very=
 bad; the US Treasury market, perhaps the most important financial market i=
n the world, should not be run on accounting gimmicks. Actually doing this =
would be terrible! On the other hand the US Treasury market, perhaps the mo=
st important financial market in the world, should not=C2=A0default, either=
. Issuing premium bonds would be bad, but the alternatives are mostly worse=
,
  [7]
=C2=A0so it=E2=80=99s worth being ready to do it.

