The aspirations of a person starting a business probably go something like =
this:
=09In the beginning, the owner makes negative money: She has to put her own=
 money into starting the business, paying its expenses, etc., and at first =
it doesn=E2=80=99t make any revenue.=09The business starts bringing in mone=
y, and it costs her less to run it.=09The business starts fully covering it=
s costs.=09The business starts more than covering its costs and paying out =
some profits to its owner,
  [8]
=C2=A0and she can use the money to pay off her credit card bills and=C2=A0b=
uy groceries.=09The business starts paying its owner more, and she can use =
the money to buy a nicer house and put her kids through college.=09The busi=
ness starts paying even more, and she can use the money for yachts and spor=
ts teams and her children=E2=80=99s documentary films.=09The business=C2=A0=
starts paying even more, and at some point she runs out of possible consump=
tion activities. At this point, it is traditional for the owner to=C2=A0dev=
ote herself to philanthropy. The profits of the business will go to fund go=
od causes that she chooses.

Well. This is not really the only model.=C2=A0This is the=C2=A0model for a =
business that (1) makes a ton of money=C2=A0and (2) never goes public. The =
main alternative is to go public at some point: The owner sells some of her=
 stake in the company to the public for cash, and then she uses the cash fo=
r yachts or philanthropy. After that,=C2=A0the company is owned by public s=
hareholders, who have an infinite appetite for profit: Any=C2=A0one=C2=A0ow=
ner can only buy so many yachts, but millions of public shareholders will n=
ever get enough yachts. And so the classical theory is that public companie=
s are supposed to maximize profits forever.
But private companies don=E2=80=99t have to do that, and there is some=C2=
=A0very loose=C2=A0sense in which anyone who starts an ambitious business t=
hat doesn=E2=80=99t take outside money=C2=A0is starting a nonprofit. =E2=80=
=9COnce I make enough profit=C2=A0to pay back my initial costs and buy thre=
e yachts, tops, the rest goes to charity, so really it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a non=
profit.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know. Anyway  here=E2=80=99s a fun st=
ory in the Information about Microsoft Corp.=E2=80=99s possible plan=C2=A0t=
o invest $10 billion in=C2=A0OpenAI:

Microsoft and OpenAI have spent months hammering out a complex deal that ai=
ms to balance their respective needs: OpenAI needs more money to keep impro=
ving its software. And so it is now willing to pay a large share of future =
profits to Microsoft and other investors=E2=80=94a necessary step given the=
 low likelihood it will try to go public. But the startup=E2=80=94whose Cha=
tGPT chatbot has taken the industry by storm=E2=80=94is proposing that it t=
ransition to nonprofit status again after it pays a certain amount of profi=
t to the investors.
After OpenAI pays back its first investors, Microsoft will get 75% of profi=
ts until its principal investment is paid back and 49% of profits after tha=
t until it hits a theoretical cap, according to a person briefed on the ter=
ms. Other investors and OpenAI employees would have similar caps on profits=
 they share. The idea of capping returns stems from OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonpro=
fit origins. =E2=80=A6
OpenAI has proposed a key concession as part of discussions with potential =
new investors. Instead of putting a hard cap on the profit sharing=E2=80=94=
essentially their return on investment=E2=80=94it could increase the cap 20=
% per year starting around 2025, said a person briefed on the change.
Investors say this compromise, if it goes through, would make the deal more=
 attractive because it would allow shareholders to obtain venture-level ret=
urns if the company becomes a moneymaker.

Absolutely magnificent stuff, taking billions of dollars of outside investm=
ent, promising =E2=80=9Cventure-level returns,=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0after that=
 you=E2=80=99re a nonprofit. Imagine the confidence you=E2=80=99d need to c=
ap returns at 20%.
The funniest (also, worst)=C2=A0outcome would be if=C2=A0every dollar that =
OpenAI makes, after it pays billions of dollars of capped profits to its=C2=
=A0investors of course, is earmarked for artificial-intelligence safety res=
earch. =E2=80=9CAs a nonprofit, we are going to invest heavily in making su=
re that our product does not eradicate humanity,=C2=A0as=C2=A0soon as we fi=
nish giving=C2=A0Microsoft a nice venture-level return on its $10 billion i=
nvestment.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And then OpenAI=E2=80=99s AI, being intelligent, r=
