<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Mint the premium=C2=A0bonds!</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The dumbest thing in economics, the US governm=
ent=E2=80=99s debt ceiling, is clattering into relevance again. Basically t=
he US Department of the Treasury has to pay the US government=E2=80=99s bil=
ls, and to do that it issues debt, and every time it issues new debt it add=
s a little to the total amount of debt outstanding, and=C2=A0eventually the=
 debt outstanding reaches some arbitrary number called=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Cde=
bt ceiling.=E2=80=9D And then Treasury can=E2=80=99t issue any more debt, u=
nless Congress raises the debt ceiling. Which it can easily do =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it=E2=80=99s just an arbitrary number! =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=A0Republica=
ns in Congress <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/302=
21555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tLzIwMjMvMDEvMTEvY29uZ3Jlc3MtZGVidC=
1jZWlsaW5nLXJpc2tzLWNvdWxkLWJlLXJlYWwtdGhpcy10aW1l/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bd3cac909" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">keep threatening not to</a>,=C2=A0and if that happens=C2=
=A0then the government=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t pay its bills and defaults on its=
 obligations. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly9ob21lLnRyZWFzdXJ5Lmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGV=
hc2VzL2p5MTEzNg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB417e59bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a recent speech<=
/a> from Assistant Secretary of the Treasury Joshua Frost with more detail =
on why the debt ceiling is dumb and why Congress should raise it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a real risk that Congress=C2=A0wo=
n=E2=80=99t, so=C2=A0today Bloomberg Opinion contributor=C2=A0<a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2xvd2JvcmluZy5jb20vcC9hLW5ldy1wbGFuLXRvLWdldC1hcm91bmQtdGhlLWRlYnQ/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB242ba0ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Matt Yglesias has a Substack column</a=
> arguing that=C2=A0Treasury should solve the problem of the debt ceiling u=
sing premium bonds. I think this is correct, I have <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFsYnJlYWtlc=
i5jb20vMjAxMy8wMS9pbnN0ZWFkLW9mLWEtdHJpbGxpb24tZG9sbGFyLXBsYXRpbnVtLWNvaW4t=
dHJlYXN1cnktc2hvdWxkLW1pbnQtYS10cmlsbGlvbi1kb2xsYXItNTAwYm4tYm9uZA/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB6a9a2ca5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">made</a> this <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTMtMTAtMDIvbWludC10aGUtcHJlbWl1bS1ib25kcy0=
_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW=
5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBdeafb0cd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> argument</a> a few times before, and Yg=
lesias clearly explains why the debt ceiling is very dumb and why Treasury =
should, if need be, use gimmicks to solve it. And as gimmicks go,=C2=A0this=
 one is fine. But his bond math is a little odd=C2=A0so I wanted to walk th=
rough a simplified version=C2=A0here.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Assume that the US Treasury, these days, can i=
ssue a one-year bond at an interest rate of 4.5%; that is not quite right b=
ut good enough.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Simplistically,=C2=A0you pay Treasury $100 today, and in a year, =
Treasury pays you back your $100, and also $4.50 of interest.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0When this bond is issued, it increases the government=E2=80=99s d=
ebt by $100, the face amount of the bond.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine a debt ceiling that worked a=
 different way: You could imagine counting this bond as adding $104.50 to t=
he debt, since that is the total amount that the government has to pay back=
 in principal and interest. But that would be sort of economically nonsensi=
cal, and anyway it is not the way the actual debt ceiling works. The actual=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzMxLzMxMDE/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB53de1f78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">US debt ceiling statute</a> caps =E2=80=9Cth=
e face amount of obligations=E2=80=9D issued or guaranteed by the governmen=
t, meaning the <em>principal=C2=A0</em>amount, not the interest it has to p=
ay. Principal repayment obligations count toward the debt ceiling; interest=
 obligations do not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course, you could pay Treasury $200 today t=
o buy=C2=A0<em>two=C2=A0</em>of these one-year, $100, 4.5% bonds. That woul=
d increase the debt stock by $200. And in a year you=E2=80=99d get back $20=
9: your $200, plus 4.5% interest on your $200.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The premium-bond gimmick is: Treasury sells yo=
u=C2=A0<em>one </em>one-year $100 bond today, with an interest rate of <em>=
109%</em>. In a year you get back $209: the $100 face amount of the bond, p=
lus 109% interest. That bond has a face amount of $100, but it is clearly=
=C2=A0<em>worth=C2=A0</em>$200 today: It is economically the same as the tw=
o 4.5% bonds from the previous paragraph. So you=E2=80=99d be willing to pa=
y Treasury $200 for it: the $100 face amount, plus $100 of =E2=80=9Cpremium=
=E2=80=9D to make the yield work out. And Treasury would be willing to sell=
 it to you for $200: It sells you this $100 bond for $200. Treasury gets $2=
00 of cash. But technically this bond is only $100 of =E2=80=9Cdebt,=E2=80=
=9D of face amount, so it only increases the debt by $100.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can do this for other maturities,=C2=A0wit=
h slightly more math. Today the 10-year Treasury note yield is about 3.6%. =
Instead of paying $100 for a 10-year Treasury note that pays a normal=C2=A0=
annual interest rate ($3.60 per year) and pays back $100 at maturity, you c=
ould pay $200 for a 10-year Treasury note that pays normal annual interest=
=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>$10 per year, and pays back $100 at maturity. You =
get your $200 back =E2=80=94=C2=A0$10 per year for 10 years plus $100 at th=
e end =E2=80=94=C2=A0plus interest on your money. But that $10 per year of =
principal return is <em>called=C2=A0</em>interest, and treated as interest =
for the debt ceiling. (The way the math actually works is that this bond wo=
uld have about a 15.6% interest rate, that is, you=E2=80=99d get back about=
 $15.60 per year plus $100 at the end.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>) It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a =E2=80=9C$100 bond=E2=80=9D for purposes of calcu=
lating how much debt is outstanding, but it=E2=80=99s worth $200.=C2=A0So, =
again, Treasury can raise $200 by selling $100 of debt.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So every time $100 of debt comes due, Treasury=
 can pay it back by selling $100 of debt for $200, keep the extra $100 to p=
ay its expenses, and render the debt ceiling irrelevant.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does this work? I have written about it a few =
times before, ages ago, and my rough sense is =E2=80=9Cmeh, sure, probably.=
=E2=80=9D Nobody <em>likes </em>it, but neither has anyone ever pointed me =
to anything that makes it=C2=A0<em>impossible</em>. Again, the=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzMxLzMxMDE/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cC53de1f78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">debt limit statute</a>=C2=A0applies to =E2=80=9Cthe =
face amount of obligations=E2=80=9D issued by the government, so a bond wit=
h a $100 face amount sold for $200 would count for only $100 of debt. The l=
aw also allows the Treasury to issue bonds =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvc=
m5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzMxLzMxMDI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9c332c7d" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">at any annual interest rate</a>,=E2=80=9D and <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNv=
cm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzMxLzMxMjE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2b749a6c" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">to decide</a> =E2=80=9Cthe offering price and interest rate=E2=80=
=9D of any issuance. So I think if the Treasury secretary said =E2=80=9Cwe=
=E2=80=99re going to sell $100 face amount of 10-year bonds for $200 and pa=
y a 15.6% interest rate on them,=E2=80=9D that is quite gimmicky but also=
=C2=A0pretty clearly=C2=A0allowed by the statute. If Treasury did it, someo=
ne would probably sue, but I don=E2=80=99t think they=E2=80=99d have a very=
 good case; the law gives Treasury a lot of flexibility.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, Treasury itself=C2=A0has rules about debt=
 issuance that do=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>really allow this; the <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuZWNmci5nb3YvY3VycmVudC90aXRsZS0zMS9zdWJ0aXRsZS1CL2NoYXB0ZXItSUkvc3ViY2hh=
cHRlci1BL3BhcnQtMzU2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8a4393b9" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">current rul=
es</a> generally require Treasury to issue notes and bonds at a price of pa=
r ($100 for a $100 face amount) or less.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But those rules are set by the Treasury and can be changed in its=
 discretion, without any act of Congress or any sort of administrative proc=
edure; the rules say: =E2=80=9CWe reserve the right to modify the terms and=
 conditions of new securities and to depart from the customary pattern of s=
ecurities offerings at any time.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main problems people have with this idea a=
re in the general category of =E2=80=9Cmarket reaction=E2=80=9D: Investors =
would not like this because it=E2=80=99s a weird gimmick, they would worry =
about it being somehow invalid, etc., so they would require higher yields a=
nd thus increase the government=E2=80=99s borrowing cost and interest rates=
 generally. It=E2=80=99s important to note that, in my simple math above, t=
he government=E2=80=99s borrowing costs have=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>increas=
ed: The 15.6% interest rate on my hypothetical 10-year bond, or the 109% in=
terest rate on my hypothetical one-year bond, do=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>rep=
resent more expensive borrowing than the current rates of 3.6% for a 10-yea=
r or 4.5% for a one-year; they just represent accounting gimmicks. In my hy=
pothetical math, Treasury is paying the same actual yields on the actual mo=
ney it raises; those high interest rates are just to shift principal repaym=
ent (covered by the debt ceiling) into interest (not covered). But in reali=
ty investors might <em>also=C2=A0</em>charge a bit more; the 10-year rate m=
ight really be, you know, 15.8%. That would be bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s hard to know how much of an effec=
t this would have; it has never happened and no one has clear intuitions fo=
r it.=C2=A0In general, very-high-premium bonds tend to be worth a bit less =
than normal bonds,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0mostly for credit reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0a bond with $100 face am=
ount and very high interest that trades at $200 will only pay back $100 in =
bankruptcy =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s not clear that that worry would =
apply to US government debt. (Similarly, people worry that high-premium Tre=
asuries would be hard to finance in the repo market, but it=E2=80=99s not o=
bvious why that would be permanently true if the market concluded that Trea=
sury was good for the money.) But investors might worry that somehow these =
bonds=C2=A0would<em>=C2=A0</em>be invalidated and they wouldn=E2=80=99t get=
 their interest payments, and that risk would require a higher yield.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway as a matter of financial engineering I =
find this fun to think about. As an actual thing for the US Treasury to do,=
 I think it is obviously very bad; the US Treasury market, perhaps the most=
 important financial market in the world, should not be run on accounting g=
immicks. Actually doing this would be terrible! On the other hand the US Tr=
easury market, perhaps the most important financial market in the world, sh=
ould not=C2=A0<em>default</em>, either. Issuing premium bonds would be bad,=
 but the alternatives are mostly worse,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"=
#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: n=
one !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-b=
lock;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0so it=E2=80=99s worth being ready to do it.</p>
