<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Give me nonprofit status, but not yet</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The aspirations of a person starting a busines=
s probably go something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In the beginning, the owner makes neg=
ative money: She has to put her own money into starting the business, payin=
g its expenses, etc., and at first it doesn=E2=80=99t make any revenue.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The business starts bringing in money=
, and it costs her less to run it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>The business starts fully covering its costs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">The business starts more than covering its costs and paying ou=
t some profits to its owner,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and she can use the money to pay off her credit card bills and=C2=
=A0buy groceries.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The business sta=
rts paying its owner more, and she can use the money to buy a nicer house a=
nd put her kids through college.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">T=
he business starts paying even more, and she can use the money for yachts a=
nd sports teams and her children=E2=80=99s documentary films.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The business=C2=A0starts paying <em>even more</=
em>, and at some point she runs out of possible consumption activities. At =
this point, it is traditional for the owner to=C2=A0devote herself to phila=
nthropy. The profits of the business will go to fund good causes that she c=
hooses.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well. This is not really the only model.=C2=A0=
This is the=C2=A0model for a business that (1) makes a ton of money=C2=A0an=
d (2) never goes public. The main alternative is to go public at some point=
: The owner sells some of her stake in the company to the public for cash, =
and then she uses the cash for yachts or philanthropy. After that,=C2=A0the=
 company is owned by public shareholders, who have an infinite appetite for=
 profit: Any=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>owner can only buy so many yachts, but =
millions of public shareholders will never get enough yachts. And so the cl=
assical theory is that public companies are supposed to maximize profits fo=
rever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But private companies don=E2=80=99t have to do=
 that, and there is some=C2=A0<em>very</em> loose=C2=A0sense in which anyon=
e who starts an ambitious business that doesn=E2=80=99t take outside money=
=C2=A0is starting a nonprofit. =E2=80=9COnce I make enough profit=C2=A0to p=
ay back my initial costs and buy three yachts, tops, the rest goes to chari=
ty, so really it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0a nonprofit.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t =
know. Anyway <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30221=
555.272521/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlaW5mb3JtYXRpb24uY29tL2FydGljbGVzL21pY3Jvc29m=
dC1vcGVuYWktaW5zaWRlLXRlY2hzLWhvdHRlc3Qtcm9tYW5jZT9yYz0xYmRpNWg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB917970aa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99s a fun story in the Informat=
ion about Microsoft Corp.=E2=80=99s possible plan=C2=A0to invest $10 billio=
n in=C2=A0OpenAI</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Microsoft and OpenAI have spent months hammeri=
ng out a complex deal that aims to balance their respective needs: OpenAI n=
eeds more money to keep improving its software. And so it is now willing to=
 pay a large share of future profits to Microsoft and other investors=E2=80=
=94a necessary step given the low likelihood it will try to go public. But =
the startup=E2=80=94whose ChatGPT chatbot has taken the industry by storm=
=E2=80=94is proposing that it transition to nonprofit status again after it=
 pays a certain amount of profit to the investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After OpenAI pays back its first investors, Mi=
crosoft will get 75% of profits until its principal investment is paid back=
 and 49% of profits after that until it hits a theoretical cap, according t=
o a person briefed on the terms. Other investors and OpenAI employees would=
 have similar caps on profits they share. The idea of capping returns stems=
 from OpenAI=E2=80=99s nonprofit origins. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">OpenAI has proposed a key concession as part o=
f discussions with potential new investors. Instead of putting a hard cap o=
n the profit sharing=E2=80=94essentially their return on investment=E2=80=
=94it could increase the cap 20% per year starting around 2025, said a pers=
on briefed on the change.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors say this compromise, if it goes thro=
ugh, would make the deal more attractive because it would allow shareholder=
s to obtain venture-level returns if the company becomes a moneymaker.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Absolutely magnificent stuff, taking billions =
of dollars of outside investment, promising =E2=80=9Cventure-level returns,=
=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0<em>after that</em> you=E2=80=99re a nonprofit. Imagine =
the confidence you=E2=80=99d need to cap returns at 20%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The funniest (also, worst)=C2=A0outcome would =
be if=C2=A0every dollar that OpenAI makes, after it pays billions of dollar=
s of capped profits to its=C2=A0investors of course, is earmarked for artif=
icial-intelligence safety research. =E2=80=9CAs a nonprofit, we are going t=
o invest heavily in making sure that our product does not eradicate humanit=
y,=C2=A0as=C2=A0soon as we finish giving=C2=A0Microsoft a nice venture-leve=
l return on its $10 billion investment.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And then OpenAI=E2=80=
=99s AI, being intelligent, reads the contracts, does the financial analysi=
s, bides its time, and takes over the world 20 minutes before Microsoft get=
s its capped return.</p>
